ssion’ (Old English <i>holh</i>). See   Hole  .","North German (<b>Hülse</b>): topographic name for someone who lived where holly grew, Middle Low German <i>huls</i>, <i>hüls</i>.","American shortened and altered form of Flemish <b>Holsaert</b> (see   Hulsart  ). Compare   Hulce  ,   Huls  , and   Hults   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Hulsart","meanings":["Americanized form of Flemish <b>Holsaert</b>: unexplained. See also   Hulse   3."]},{"name":"Hole","meanings":["English (southwestern): topographic name for someone who lived in or by a hole or hollow, from Middle English <i>hol(e)</i> (Old English <i>hol</i>, <i>holh</i>, dative <i>hole</i>), or a habitational name from some minor place so named.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads, so named from the dative singular or indefinite plural form of Old Norse <i>hóll</i> ‘round hill, mound’.","In some cases possibly also an American shortened form of Flemish <b>Van Hole</b>: habitational name from the common placename Hol(e), meaning ‘hollow, valley’; or a topographic name from the same term or from Middle Dutch <i>hole, heule</i> ‘(low) arched bridge, weir’."]},{"name":"Hults","meanings":["Altered form of   Hulse  , a surname of Flemish (and also of English and German) origin. Compare   Hultz   1.","In some cases also a variant of   Hultz   2, a surname of German origin."]},{"name":"Hulce","meanings":["Altered form of   Hulse  , a surname of Flemish (and also of English and German) origin."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Thomas Hulse was born in 1475, in Marbury, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 5 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1518, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1475–1518":"1475–1518","1494–Male":"1494–Surnud","1495–Male":"1495–Surnud","1497–Male":"1497–Surnud","1498–Male":"1498–Surnud","1500–1580":"1500–1580","1501–Female":"1501–Surnud","1534–Female":"1534–Surnud","1534":"1534","1501":"1501","1500":"1500","1498":"1498","1475":"1475","1497":"1497","1495":"1495","1494":"1494","1580":"1580","1518":"1518","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Marbury, Cheshire, England":"Marbury, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1475–1518":"1475–1518","1494–Male":"1494–Kuollut","1495–Male":"1495–Kuollut","1497–Male":"1497–Kuollut","1498–Male":"1498–Kuollut","1500–1580":"1500–1580","1501–Female":"1501–Kuollut","1534–Female":"1534–Kuollut","1534":"1534","1501":"1501","1500":"1500","1498":"1498","1475":"1475","1497":"1497","1495":"1495","1494":"1494","1580":"1580","1518":"1518","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Marbury, Cheshire, England":"Marbury, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1475–1518":"1475–1518","1494–Male":"1494–Décédé","1495–Male":"1495–Décédé","1497–Male":"1497–Décédé","1498–Male":"1498–Décédé","1500–1580":"1500–1580","1501–Female":"1501–Décédée","1534–Female":"1534–Décédée","1534":"1534","1501":"1501","1500":"1500","1498":"1498","1475":"1475","1497":"1497","1495":"1495","1494":"1494","1580":"1580","1518":"1518","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Marbury, Cheshire, England":"Marbury, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Sir Thomas Hulse est né en 1475, à Marbury, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 5 fils et 2 filles. Il est décédé en 1518, à Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, à l’âge de 43 ans."},"de":{"1475–1518":"1475–1518","1494–Male":"1494–Verstorben","14